title: For Sale:  RARE 1887 Bayonet Trapdoor Rifle
postcontent: DARE SPRINGFIELD MODEL 1887 EXPERIMENTAL ROD BAYONET TRAPDOOR RIFLE. Cal. 45-70. Very rare bayonet with 32-5/8″ bbl, fixed hood over the front sight which has an internal 2-position blade as part of the hood and 1,400 yard Buffington rear sight without marking. Bbl has the usual “V”, “P” and eagle proofs. Mounted in a 1-pc, full length walnut stock with straight grip and musket buttplate with trap. Left side of the wrist has a clear “SWP / 1887” cartouche. Forestock is secured with two bands with the upper band having stacking & sling wires with another sling wire on the trigger guard & brass hook. Bottom front of the bbl is equipped with the 1884-style ramrod bayonet attachment that has straight edge and flat ears that lock the rod bayonet in place. This style is the predecessor to the Model 1888 which had wrap-around locking ears. Bayonet is a rnd steel rod with knurled section at the end with dimpled tip. According to Flayderman’s Guide to Antique American Firearms there were only 1,000 of these rare rifles produced. Referenced publication states “The production run was made for trial use and distribution was wide spread. Survival rate is quite small. Very scarce.”. According to The .45-70 Springfield Book II 1865-1893, Frasca, there were actually 1,013 of these rifles produced, Very few of these rare rifles are known today in orig configuration. According to the Frasca book, after the trials, most of the rifles were dismantled and serviceable parts were salvaged and used in the production of the Model 1888 rifle. CONDITION: Very good. Steel parts retain a dark attic patina with some blue showing through and moderate pitting over the top exposed surfaces. Stock has a few light bruises, nicks & scratches, otherwise is sound and retains a cleaned oiled finish. Mechanics are fine, brilliant shiny bore. No Sling (3,000-5,000)

title: For Sale:  Glock 19 MOS Gen 4  9mm IN STOCK
postcontent: In stock now at Deadeye for only $599  The Glock 19 Modular Optic System (MOS) The MOS models come from the factory with a slot milled out of the top of the slide just forward of the rear sight dovetail. The slot is just about two inches long and maybe 3/16 inches deep if you remove the cover and included optics mounting plates. The gun comes with a “cover” plate installed which basically fills this gap completely, so at a glance, the Glock 19 MOS looks like a regular Glock 19 Gen 4 model, except for the visible seams. Glock 19 Modular Optic System Pistol MOS To mount an optic directly to the slide, you simply remove the cover plate and replace it with one of four included adapter plates. These plates are clearly numbered one to four and are cut with posts and holes specific to a variety of optics mounting systems. Compatible optics (at this time) include:  Plate 1: Docter, Meopta, Insight Plate 2: Trijicon Plate 3: C-More Plate 4: Leupold  For my test of the Glock 19 MOS I used a Trijicon RMR RM01 and mounted it to the G19 MOS using plate number two. Installation took less than a couple of minutes and Glock includes an Allen wrench and extra screws used to remove the cover plate and install the correct adapter plate. Once the right adapter plate in installed, just mount the Trijicon RMR (or optic of your choice) to the plate and you’re off to the races. Read more: http://www.ammoland.com/2016/01/glock-19-mos-pistol-modular-optic-system/#ixzz4KopFqhSG Under Creative Commons License: Attribution Follow us: @Ammoland on Twitter | Ammoland on Facebook

It is my very favorite gun...but due to the crap circumstances of life and the fact that Brown County wants to screw me without the courtesy of a reach around, they are now garnishing my wages to 50%... which means I'm taking home like 450$ every two weeks to live on and pay bills and what not...not to mention taking care of my kid (which I have been primarily doing since he was born but the state of Minnesota doesn't give a damn on account of his mother not working much.)    So, I am now selling all of my toys. I don't want to but I'm going to do it anyway because my son is worth it. M+M M10 AKM based on Romanian parts and built by a company in Colorado. I have had probably around 500 rounds through it and she never skipped a beat. It's got a quad rail, adjustable rear and front sights, angled fore grip, intafuse folding stock (NATO length), hogue grip (it's a thing of beauty holding this grip) and tapco trigger (bump fires like an animal)  This will come with many magazines including 2 Norinco 40 rounders, 3 tapco/magpul poly mags, and a Korean steel thirty rounder. I also have the old tapco stock and sight alignment tool. Installed a recoil buffer also. It comes with the carrying soft case and a dry box of mixed ammo (Tula, Wolf, ect...don't remember how many rounds but probably like another five hundred or so)   This firearm has been meticulously maintained...even though it's an AK and you don't really need to lol... (I've seen these things buried in the dirt for 10 years and then taken out and used again...tank tracks being used to bend the barrel straight after some kind of bend...and torture tested on YouTube (seriously check that out).   Bottom line is, if you want to have a firearm that's reliable and cheap to shoot....and will probably last till Jesus comes back...this is what you need. title: For Sale:  CZ 527 .223/5.56
postcontent: Hi guys, I'm putting up for sale a beloved safe queen, my CZ 527 Carbine (the carbine version comes with iron sights). If you're reading this, you likely already know how sweet these rifles are, and what amazing stuff CZ puts out, in general. I'm the original owner, it's in pristine condition, and it's only been to the range 2,maybe 3 times, with a total round count of well under a hundred rounds. It's basically still brand new. This thing is scary accurate, with numerous ammos, from 40 to 62 gr. A big plus with the CZ .223's is that they are one of the few rifles around that are OK'd by the factory to shoot mil-spec 5.56 ammo, which opens your options a bit. These rifles also have a "set trigger", but I've found it to be extremely sensitive, and I never had any complaints with the normal trigger. But for a single shot fired with the irons when I first got it (a buddy of mine hit a squirrel at 65 yards, that I couldn't even see!), it's always had this scope on it, a Bushnell Elite 4200 3-9x40. In case you're not familiar with them, Bushnell's Elite series came about when Bushnell bought out the highly respected Bausch & Lomb company, and continued manufacture under their Elite name. These are not your Wal-mart blister-pack Bushnells, they are basically their premium line, kinda like Lexus is to Toyota. The Bushnell Elites are all very nice scopes, made in Japan, w/ fully multi-coated lenses, lifetime warranty, magnum-recoil rated, yadda,yadda. The scope rings are steel CZ's  (very high quality rings that didn't originally come with the rifle, I bought them seperately). As you can see, i still have the original box and paperwork, for both rifle and scope. Also included is a load of various .223 ammos: 50-rd box of Fiocchi Extrema polymer-tipped V-max, a couple boxes of 62-gr Silver bear, a box of Federal American Eagle, a box of Remingtons, and a bag of loose Fiocchi Extrema V-max. That's all the relevant info that comes to mind,feel free to ask any further questions. I might consider some trades +cash, but I mostly need the cash, and my interests at the moment are pretty limited (early gen3 G17 or 19, Ruger SP101 2"). Thanks for looking.........almost forgot, please respond with enough detail that I can tell you're a legitimate local buyer and not another scammer, or I just won't respond. Buyer/trader must be Georgia resident, over age 18, with ID. As always, I'll happilly show my Ga DL and carry permit.

title: For Sale:  AR-15 300 Blackout 7.5" Pistol
postcontent: The 300 blackout chambered AR pistol offers superior ballistics in a compact package, making for a great trunk gun, backpacking gun, home defense, etc. Basically, this round hits like an AK but pops more like a 9mm, which is why these guns run great supressed. Blackout ammo prices keep falling (found some for about 40 cents/round the other day) and the 300 blackout seems to be taking over the short-barreled and/or suppressed AR market. The 7.5 inch length is great when you really need to be high-speed/low-drag/compact, and 300 blackout is the caliber to do it in because of the minimal barrel length that is needed to achieve a great terminal ballistic effect. In about 15-20 min with an armorers wrench you can swap the barrel and be shooting 5.56/.223. The magazines, the bolt, everything else is the same. This gun shoots very nice and is easy to become proficient at, especially with the single point sling. Selling for financial reasons. This AR only has about 60 rounds through it. It's not even fully broken in yet. This is priced to sell. I don't expect it to last long.
